Peace on Earth 🕊️ can only come from Accountability and taking *Responsibility* for how our behavior affects other people & the world around us! There is NOTHING peaceful about being SILENT and content with injustices. Nothing. You may not always like or understand the things I post. They may be triggering and they really should be, because in doing so it brings up what we need to heal within ourselves.
There’s bigger, more productive, conversations to have than explosive arguments. The more we can talk to eachother without reacting from emotion (it’s not to say we shouldn’t ever feel emotion) but our emotions are (OURS) they are not the plight of our children or others. We need to take responsibility for them. ♥️

My moms favorite saying was “Don’t respond, let it go in one ear and out the other” -> I said FVCK that! …  My favorite saying is: Silence is Violence…. Hold other people accountable for their behavior. I don’t care how temporarily uncomfortable it might be. It’s a vital ingredient to holding boundaries of respect for yourself. You may never be validated for the trauma handed to you. But from your strength in standing up for yourself assertively, calmly and matter of factly regardless, you are standing up for that little child and being the parental figure you needed to protect you. Just by saying “no” “not ok” and “enough is enough” ♥️🕊️🐐#thescapegoatprevails #peacefulintentions #peacelovevibes

I’ve gotten to the point where I don’t care if people think I’m crazy or they don’t want to understand my humanity as a female. I’m done hiding and being afraid to speak my truth and be proud of who I am. We can only experience the world through our own level of perceptive openness. Step one to opening that perception is realizing everyone is broken. Just on different levels of accepting that. We are all running from things but how perceptive are you of what that is?

When you go out into the woods, and you look at trees, you see all these different trees. And some of them are bent, and some of them are straight, and some of them are evergreens, and some of them are whatever. And you look at the tree and you allow it. You see why it is the way it is. You sort of understand that it didn’t get enough light, and so it turned that way. And you don’t get all emotional about it. You just allow it. You appreciate the tree.

The minute you get near humans, you lose all that. And you are constantly saying ‘You are too this, or I’m too this.’ That judgment mind comes in. And so I practice turning people into trees. Which means appreciating them just the way they are.
🌳 Ram Dass

Rare are those that can see beyond themselves 🛶 and realize they are not boats or islands in the ocean but one with the entire ocean. One who knows that the ‘other’ selves need boundaries with their love and kindness in order to sustain themselves in homeostasis. The illusion of separateness pits us against eachother. It creates bitterness, selfishness, and disrespect. We stop communicating thinking the world is bad and out to hurt us. We abuse and ignore what’s around us to fuel our own egos and then end up living a very empty existence full of regret due to lack of accountability for oneself. Too much comfort kills us as does too much chaos. But a balance of the push and pull is what facilitates our growth. Can you imagine how differently we would treat the world and each other if we all woke up to this fact? See the karma in all life. Love others because we love ourselves. But boundaries are also loving others because once we dissolve our fear of rejection and of not being liked for speaking our truth… Mothers no longer model to their daughters to be these puppets in mental shackles… while the earth burns. - Alanna || image quote Via @subconsciousthinkers

social_posts.post_text: I get often asked (by men) why I don’t smile in my pictures or them telling me how I ‘should’ smile. If I’m honest, which I try to always be… it’s very condescending. I don’t believe in victim mentality, but at the same time you don’t know what someone has been through or experienced in their life and why they find it hard to smile in photos. If you don’t feel smiley inside, being told to by someone pointing it out, just makes you feel worse, not better. I’ve been struggling for the past few weeks with illness after illness. The joys of having a preschooler. It also has made me feel very depressed that living in my body feels so uncomfortable. But it also made me realize to some degree I always feel uncomfortable in my body due to anxiety I still dont fully understand after years and years of therapy. It doesn’t help how isolating motherhood is on its own and having no support system. No mother myself. In short, if you see someone not smiling, be the reason they smile. Give them a reason. Rather than telling them that they ‘should’

Reflecting back on the past year and how life changing it’s been. Palau 🇵🇼 was definitely top on the list. The only reason I was able to go there was because I allowed myself to be terrified and feel the risk of doing something I’ve never done before. Overcoming an ancestral hurdle. I learned so much studying Sustainable Resource Management and working with the local conservation groups dedicated to protecting and enriching the reef. I both was in heaven and in hell in many ways. I’ve learned world travels are never boring nor one dimensional.. I struggled both with the detachment of leaving my daughter for over 2 weeks to embark on this journey, knowing it would be inspiring to her to see her mom living a full life and exploring and taking risks (which I never got to see my mother do). I also formed a great attachment to the reef and all its creatures. I was the last one out of the water on nearly every excursion, but especially that last day out with Paddling Palau. I cried on Scott’s birthday as our speedboat heading back for the dock. I knew and could fully sit with the grief of how much love and awe I felt for nature in that place. The group dynamics were something else that was tough for me. I had a hard time saying goodbye to everyone and formed attachments to certain people and left a lot of things unsaid with others. There was this push and pull with boys in the group as well as girls. This feeling of not fitting in, to then laughing harder than I’ve laughed since I was a kid. Compliments and friendship to bullying, jealousy, and abandonment by what I thought was a friend, in bar full of Navy men wondering which of them I’d choose to spend the evening with. I’ve got stories. But the overarching theme was overcoming myself. Not sinking or hiding. But facing my fears and sitting with them so I could open up new doors not only for myself but for my daughter. Because she had the example. I hope for my Aria that she grows up to be both a conservationist and a world traveler. I hope to teach her how to sit with her anxieties and go beyond them to do great things. I hope she can learn to feel both the grief and the blessings of being alive and never go numb.
